    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1243943849" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1243943849" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3403278-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604899399p2/3403278.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1243943849?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/3403278-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781554680924" href="/book/show/2767171-weaveworld">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=surrealism">surrealism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=zz1987">zz1987</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=aa-englandlit">aa-englandlit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=xlong-over-400">xlong-over-400</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=aa-europelit">aa-europelit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=all-five-star">all-five-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=art">art</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3403278-michael?shelf=aaa-favoritefiction">aaa-favoritefiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1243943849" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16259376473520801534">290220: well i have not read any more barker to finish but perhaps that is so i do not become disappointed...<br/><br/>020515: this is a later addition: thinking about this some more. though i have many other works to read i will get to barker&apos;s &apos;imajica&apos; soon, but then decided to rec this to all without edit my various e-friends on GR. this is not my usual literature nor philosophy. i did very much enjoy this. i hope this works for others...<br/><br/>first review: well. this novel, this world, this plot, all engag</span>
  <span id="freeText16259376473520801534" style="display:none">290220: well i have not read any more barker to finish but perhaps that is so i do not become disappointed...<br /><br />020515: this is a later addition: thinking about this some more. though i have many other works to read i will get to barker's 'imajica' soon, but then decided to rec this to all without edit my various e-friends on GR. this is not my usual literature nor philosophy. i did very much enjoy this. i hope this works for others...<br /><br />first review: well. this novel, this world, this plot, all engaged me far beyond what was expected. i have had this book, heard of this book, for some time- reading some of barker's books of blood did not encourage me- so there was no urgency, though as i look at it now, wonder what i would have thought of it had i read it years ago...<br /><br />would i have found, for example, thinking of all other mundane fantasies- tech, culture, politics, all medieval- such great pleasure that it is not that sort, would i have found it spurring my critical thoughts in a way mundane mundane lit almost never does- where what interests me most is how the story is told, not what the story is- would i have thought of the philosophical impression of this vivid strangeness, would i have thought of... Schopenhauer?<br /><br />this is an odd favourite, in some ways, as it is very long, is not uniquely told but rather transparently and openly as any non- genre writing. it does have some arresting images, likeable characters, understandable bad characters, lightly given metaphysics surrounding the magic weaves, the magic raptures, the mature love, fallible memories, prejudices, but none of this relies too much on say Christian worldview. i am not a particularly fast reader, i have read long books before but rarely search one out, i rarely find the pages slip by so quickly. on the other: i read this in one day, yes all 736 pages, in a few sittings, and my interest never flagged, my attention never wandered, so this must be some sort of rec. part of the pleasure of reading this was doubtless novelty and low expectations. now, i just might read it again, at a slower, more thoughtful pace...<br /><br />for this single long novel allowed me such pleasure, far beyond what gained in reading parts, never wholes, of the usual epic fantasy series. i understand barker is unique, though was rec'd lovecraft and Clark Ashton Smith, and in my reading was drawn to compare with Ben Okri, the Nigerian author just read, three books of the famished road series which are basically one long book divided in three. and of course Tolkien. and then Stephen King, an author whose fantasy works to which many friends direct me, but i enjoyed barker far more than anything by King. so this is once again reason to search out work i might never have heard of, i looked at, i searched for, as barker is not a lit award winner...<br /><br />that the world is magical beyond what we sense, is a common fantasy trope. that this need not be a universe starkly divided into capital G good and capital E evil- this is more mature, more interesting, and that this world, woven rug in our common world, is experienced through our ordinary-ish avatars, descendant of poet and descendant of witch, is much more involving than quests or use of magic or big sword. i had not expected this. i was pleasantly surprised. my day was otherwise empty yes, but i could have read something like this word count in three or four books rather than this one. it made me wonder, happily, how this would read to say the Nigerians who read Okri. it made me happy to discover another seam of precious fantasy metal that was not the familiar quasi-medieval, that had complex, real, sort of ordinary characters..,<br /><br />in recollection, after a day's thought, i smile thinking of that evil portal/character named primarily as a Salesman, i think of the coat of promises to be broken, desires captured only to be redoubled pain of losing, i think of the engendered children of the evil witch sisters, i think of the railroad train timetable and its fortuitous use, i think of the tantalizing glimpses of the woven world, the orchard of fruit you never get at the usual grocers, the horror of the very ground beneath your feet cracking open, all, all the surreal, the terrors and the delights, i think finally of how this our mundane world of snow, cold, blizzard, can only compound the fantastical horrors coming after us...<br /><br />so i guess i will try some more barker. someday return to this one. search perhaps fruitlessly for something similar...</span>
  <a data-text-id="16259376473520801534" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


